<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-275-214  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 275 214.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 27 1989 v3 n9 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army to develop awesome missile: imaging infrared AWS-M weapon tobe used against tanks.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reed, Fred.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Army plans to develop an imaging infrared, next-generation,anti-tank missile called the Advanced Anti-Tank WeaponSystem-Medium (AWS-M).andP;  Marin Marietta Corp and Texas InstrumentsInc will produce the system.andP;  The missile, which is fired from theshoulder, has a classified range in excess of 2,000 meters andweighs about 42 pounds.andP;  Advantages of AWS-M over current missilesis that its computer control allows it to fly high enough to hit atank's top armor, its infrared imaging lets the gunner see targetsclearly at night and through smoke, and its on-board computer andsensors seek the target with no further attention from the gunner.andO;AWS-M's disadvantages include the high price of thermal imagers,and a soldier must be close enough to see a target in order to useAWS-M.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Texas Instruments Inc. (contracts)Martin Marietta Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    ML; TXN.andO;Topic:     WeaponsMissilesProduct DevelopmentInfrared TechnologyImaging TechnologyUnited States. ArmyDefense Contracts.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>